      "title": "Combination of Different Foods for the Minimum Measure (Kizayit)",
      "display_title": "Food Combination",
      "timestamp": "00:07",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Kol HaOchlin Mistarfin: All foods combine for the minimum size",
          "display_title": "Kol HaOchlin",
          "timestamp": "00:07"
        },
        {
          "title": "Achal Umtza: Salt and meat combine despite salt not being considered food independently",
          "display_title": "Salt & Meat",
          "timestamp": "00:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tzir al Gabi Yerek: Sauce on vegetables combines and is considered food",
          "display_title": "Sauce",
          "timestamp": "01:28"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Achila Gassa: Overeating and Forced Consumption as Non-Eating",
      "display_title": "Achila Gassa",
      "timestamp": "03:27",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Definition of Achila Gassa: Forced eating when already satiated does not constitute eating",
          "display_title": "Definition",
          "timestamp": "03:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mai Taama - Asher Lo Te'uneh: The rationale from the principle of affliction",
          "display_title": "Mai Taama",
          "timestamp": "03:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Prat L'Mazik: Exclusion for eating that damages the food and oneself",
          "display_title": "Prat L'Mazik",
          "timestamp": "03:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Application to Terumah: Non-priest eating Terumah through achila gassa",
          "display_title": "Terumah",
          "timestamp": "05:01"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Non-Standard Modes of Consumption: Chewing Raw Grain and Swallowing Whole",
      "display_title": "Non-Standard Eating",
      "timestamp": "06:39",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Zar Shekoses Se'orim: Non-priest chewing raw barley does not constitute eating",
          "display_title": "Chewing Grain",
          "timestamp": "06:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Zar Shebala Shezifin: Swallowing prunes whole constitutes eating; regurgitation and re-eating by another",
          "display_title": "Prunes",
          "timestamp": "07:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "Status of Regurgitated Food: Once swallowed, object is acquired; regurgitated object loses food status",
          "display_title": "Regurgitated Status",
          "timestamp": "08:29"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Food and Drink Do Not Combine for Yom Kippur Purposes",
      "display_title": "Food & Drink",
      "timestamp": "11:31",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "HaOchel VeHaShoteh Ein Mistarfin: Food and drink do not combine for minimum size",
          "display_title": "Don't Combine",
          "timestamp": "11:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehoshua's Principle: Things combine only if tumah and measure are identical",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yehoshua",
          "timestamp": "11:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Distinction from Tumah Laws: Yom Kippur is about psychological reality, not formalistic categories",
          "display_title": "Psychological Reality",
          "timestamp": "14:46"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Single Korban for Combined Eating and Drinking in One Forgetting",
      "display_title": "Single Korban",
      "timestamp": "19:36",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Achal VeShata Be'E'lem Echad: Food and drink together in one state of forgetfulness bring one korban",
          "display_title": "One Aveira",
          "timestamp": "19:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "Achal Ume'lacah: Eating and work are separate prohibitions requiring two korbans",
          "display_title": "Two Aveiros",
          "timestamp": "21:32"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Eating and Drinking Non-Fit Foods and Liquids",
      "display_title": "Non-Fit Food",
      "timestamp": "21:52",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Achal Ochlin She'Einam Re'uyim: Consumption of unfit food is exempt from punishment",
          "display_title": "Unfit Food",
          "timestamp": "21:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tzir o Moryes: Fish brine and fish fat as examples of non-potable liquids",
          "display_title": "Fish Brine",
          "timestamp": "22:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Question of Azharah (Negative Prohibition) for Fasting",
      "display_title": "Azharah",
      "timestamp": "22:27",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Reish Lakish: Why no explicit negative prohibition in Torah for fasting?",
          "display_title": "No Explicit Lav",
          "timestamp": "22:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Inability to Express Prohibition Grammatically: The Torah could not elegantly state 'don't not fast'",
          "display_title": "Grammar Problem",
          "timestamp": "24:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Implied Prohibition: Despite not being explicitly stated, the negative prohibition is implied",
          "display_title": "Implied Lav",
          "timestamp": "25:17"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Derivation of Negative Prohibition from Gezeirah Shavah with Melacha",
      "display_title": "Gezeirah Shavah",
      "timestamp": "27:30",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Baraita's Derivation: Linking punishment for melacha to punishment for eating via shared terminology",
          "display_title": "Linking Punishments",
          "timestamp": "27:30"
        },
        {
          "title": "Kol VeChomer Logic: If melacha brings kareth, fasting should too; and vice versa",
          "display_title": "Kal VaChomer",
          "timestamp": "30:24"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mufneh (Extra Word): One of the prohibitions must be extra to enable the gezeirah shavah",
          "display_title": "Mufneh",
          "timestamp": "35:33"
        },
        {
          "title": "Multiple Phrasings: Five instances of melacha language to enable the link to eating",
          "display_title": "Five Instances",
          "timestamp": "39:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Alternative Derivations of Negative Prohibition for Fasting",
      "display_title": "Alternatives",
      "timestamp": "41:01",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Acha bar Yaakov: Linking inuy to Shabbat Bereishit via Shabbat Shabbaton language",
          "display_title": "Shabbat Link",
          "timestamp": "41:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Pappa: The word Shabbat inherently carries negative prohibition meaning",
          "display_title": "Intrinsic Meaning",
          "timestamp": "41:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "Dor Shel Tanai: The word Shabbat itself teaches the prohibition without external comparison",
          "display_title": "Word Meaning",
          "timestamp": "42:10"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tosefet Yom Kippur: Adding from Weekday to Holy Day",
      "display_title": "Tosefet",
      "timestamp": "43:06",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Ve'Innisem Et Nafshoseichem BeTisha: Fasting begins on the ninth evening",
          "display_title": "Ninth Evening",
          "timestamp": "43:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Me'Erev Ad Erev: From evening to evening indicating addition before and after the day",
          "display_title": "Evening to Evening",
          "timestamp": "43:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Extension from Yom Kippur: The principle of tosefet applied to all Shabbat and Yom Tov",
          "display_title": "Extension",
          "timestamp": "44:33"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Kol HaOchel VeShoTeh BeTisha: Eating on the Ninth Counts as Fasting",
      "display_title": "Eating Counts",
      "timestamp": "46:26",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Teaching That Eating on the Ninth Constitutes Fasting for Yom Kippur",
          "display_title": "Ninth Eating",
          "timestamp": "46:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conceptual Understanding: Fasting is about freedom from physicality, not merely suffering",
          "display_title": "Concept",
          "timestamp": "47:14"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ke'Illu His'anna: Appropriate eating beforehand enhances the fast spiritually",
